      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "b65ecdba5228d424",
        "text": "In his presentation of the project Le Supermarché des Images (The Supermarket of Images), Peter Szendy writes that “we live in a world that is increasingly saturated with images”—there are too many, and there is not space for all of them. Back in 2011, in his installation Photography in Abundance, Erik Kessels stacked a room with a million photos that had been uploaded to Flickr in twenty-four hours, showing this in a tangible way. When does the abundance of images become excessive, to the point of saturation? Compared to previous eras, how is our social space overloaded as if it “can no longer contain the images that constitute it”?"
